      "solution": "✅ **Correct Answer: (D) Brahmagupta**\n\n📚 **NCERT Mapping:** Class 11 Physics | Chapter 8 — Gravitation | Topic: Historical development of gravitational theory; Indian contributions to science\n\n⭐ **Exam Relevance: High** — Indian ancient scientists and their contributions to physics is a recurring theme in competitive exams, especially IAS and DRDO CEPTAM General Awareness + Science sections.\n\n---\n\n**Brahmagupta (598–668 CE)** was an Indian mathematician and astronomer who anticipated the concept of gravity centuries before Newton. In his work **Brahmasphutasiddhanta (628 CE)**, he wrote:\n\n*\"All heavy things are attracted toward the Earth\"* — essentially describing gravitational attraction.\n\nHe also stated that the Earth attracts all bodies toward its centre — a remarkable insight for the 7th century CE, about 1000 years before Newton's formal mathematical law.\n\n---\n\n**(A) Aryabhatta (476–550 CE) — INCORRECT:**\nAryabhatta was a brilliant mathematician and astronomer who calculated π, proposed the heliocentric model, and explained eclipses. However, it was **Brahmagupta**, not Aryabhatta, who specifically articulated that all things gravitate to the Earth.\n\n**(B) Varahamihira (505–587 CE) — INCORRECT:**\nVarahamihira was an Indian polymath who worked in astronomy, astrology, and natural sciences. He made contributions to encyclopaedic works but is not specifically credited with anticipating Newton's gravitational concept.\n\n**(C) Buddhagupta — INCORRECT:**\nBuddhagupta was a Gupta dynasty emperor (reign c. 476–495 CE), not a scientist or astronomer. Not associated with gravitational concepts.\n\n**(D) Brahmagupta — CORRECT:**\nBrahmagupta explicitly wrote about gravitational attraction to Earth in 628 CE. He is credited with anticipating Newton's concept of universal gravitation by more than a thousand years.\n\n**Timeline for DRDO exam:**\n- Brahmagupta: 628 CE (declared all things gravitate to Earth)\n- Newton: 1687 CE (Universal Law of Gravitation — F = Gm₁m₂/r²)\n\n🔬 **DRDO Relevance:** India's ancient scientific heritage is an important part of DRDO CEPTAM General Science and General Awareness sections. Understanding Indian contributions to science also provides context for DRDO's pride in indigenous defence research."
