      "solution": "✅ **Correct Answer: (C) Move along with the spaceship at the same speed**\n\n📚 **NCERT Mapping:** Class 11 Physics | Chapter 8 — Gravitation | Topic: Orbital velocity; weightlessness; free fall in orbit\n\n⭐ **Exam Relevance: Very High** — Orbital mechanics and the behaviour of objects released from satellites is a classic conceptual question. Tests deep understanding of weightlessness and orbital motion. Frequently appears in UPSC IAS and DRDO CEPTAM.\n\n---\n\n**Why the apple moves with the spaceship at the same speed:**\n\nWhen the spaceship is in orbit, it is in a state of **continuous free fall** around the Earth — both the spaceship and the apple are subject to the same gravitational acceleration at the same altitude.\n\n**Orbital velocity** depends on altitude (distance from Earth), not on mass:\n**v_orbital = √(GM/r)**\n\nSince both the apple and the spaceship are at the **same altitude (r)**, they have the **same orbital velocity**. When the apple is released, it continues to orbit at the same speed and altitude as the spaceship — it doesn't fall down or speed up or slow down. They remain together.\n\n**This is exactly analogous to weightlessness:** Both are in free fall together — neither is 'heavier' nor 'lighter' than the other in orbital context.\n\n---\n\n**(A) Fall towards the Earth — INCORRECT:**\nThe apple would fall toward Earth only if it were at rest and then released. Since both spaceship and apple are already in orbit (moving horizontally at orbital velocity), releasing the apple does not change its trajectory — it continues in the same orbit.\n\n**(B) Move at a lower speed — INCORRECT:**\nThe apple does not slow down when released. In the vacuum of space (no air resistance) and at the same orbital altitude, the apple maintains the same orbital speed.\n\n**(C) Move along with the spaceship at the same speed — CORRECT:**\nReleasing an object from an orbiting spacecraft does not change its orbital conditions. Both the apple and the spaceship have the same orbital velocity at the same altitude. The apple simply continues alongside the spaceship.\n\n**(D) Move at a higher speed — INCORRECT:**\nThere is no force to accelerate the apple beyond the spaceship's speed upon release. No thrust is applied, and gravity acts equally on both.\n\n🔬 **DRDO Relevance:** This principle is critical for DRDO's satellite-based systems — deploying instruments or releasing sub-satellites from a mother satellite. Objects released from DRDO-associated satellites (reconnaissance, communication) follow the same orbital mechanics — they continue in the same orbit unless given a velocity change (delta-v)."
