      "solution": "✅ **Correct Answer: (D) The vertical line through the centre of gravity of the tower falls within its base**\n\n📚 **NCERT Mapping:** Class 11 Physics | Chapter 7 — System of Particles and Rotational Motion | Topic: Centre of gravity; stability of bodies; conditions for equilibrium\n\n⭐ **Exam Relevance: Very High** — Centre of gravity and stability is a high-scoring topic in DRDO CEPTAM and IAS. This famous example appears in NCERT and all major competitive exam resources.\n\n---\n\n**Principle of Stability:**\n\nA body remains stable (does not topple) as long as the **vertical line drawn through its centre of gravity (CG) falls within its base of support**.\n\nWhen this vertical line falls **outside** the base, the body becomes unstable and topples over.\n\n**The Leaning Tower of Pisa:**\n- Despite leaning at an angle (~5.5° from vertical), the tower's CG is positioned such that the vertical line through CG still falls **within the boundaries of its base (foundation)**\n- Therefore, the net torque due to gravity tends to restore it (or at least doesn't cause it to fall)\n- The tower is stable because the tilting hasn't gone far enough to push the CG line outside the base\n\n---\n\n**(A) It is tapered at the top — INCORRECT:**\nThe tower being tapered at the top lowers the CG slightly, which helps stability, but this alone is NOT the reason it doesn't fall. The primary reason is the CG line staying within the base.\n\n**(B) It covers a large base area — INCORRECT:**\nA large base area increases stability margin (harder to topple), but the tower's base area is not exceptionally large. The specific reason it doesn't fall is the CG vertical line staying within the base — not the absolute size of the base.\n\n**(C) Its CG remains at the lowest position — INCORRECT:**\nThe CG of the Leaning Tower is NOT at the lowest position — it is at a considerable height. A body at its lowest CG position would be like a ball on the floor. The tower's CG is elevated. This option is factually wrong.\n\n**(D) Vertical line through CG falls within base — CORRECT:**\nThis is the precise scientific reason. The tower leans but as long as the vertical from its CG falls within the base perimeter, gravitational torque does not cause it to topple. Engineers have reinforced the foundation to ensure this remains the case.\n\n**General rule:** If vertical from CG → within base = stable. Outside base = topples.\n\n🔬 **DRDO Relevance:** Centre of gravity calculations are critical in DRDO for military vehicle design (tank stability on slopes), missile CG calculations (must be properly placed for stable flight), and design of military structures and bridges for combat zones."
