      "solution": "✅ **Correct Answer: (C) One-fourth of what it is now**\n\n📚 **NCERT Mapping:** Class 11 Physics | Chapter 8 — Gravitation | Topic: Newton's Universal Law of Gravitation — inverse square law\n\n⭐ **Exam Relevance: Very High** — Inverse square law calculations for gravitational force are among the most frequently tested numericals in DRDO CEPTAM, UPSC, and all state PSC physics sections. Simple formula application.\n\n---\n\n**Applying Newton's Law of Gravitation:**\n\n**F = G × M_sun × M_earth / r²**\n\nCurrently: F₁ = G × M_s × M_e / r²\n\nIf distance becomes 2r:\nF₂ = G × M_s × M_e / (2r)² = G × M_s × M_e / 4r²\n\n**F₂ / F₁ = (1/4r²) / (1/r²) = 1/4**\n\n**F₂ = F₁ / 4 = One-fourth of original force**\n\n**The inverse square law: F ∝ 1/r²**\nIf distance doubles (×2), force becomes 1/2² = **1/4 times** the original.\n\n---\n\n**(A) Twice as large — INCORRECT:**\nThis would apply if force were proportional to distance (F ∝ r) — but gravity follows the INVERSE square law, not direct proportion.\n\n**(B) Four times as large — INCORRECT:**\nForce would be four times larger if the distance were HALVED (r → r/2). Here the distance is DOUBLED, so force decreases.\n\n**(C) One-fourth of original — CORRECT:**\nDistance doubled → r² becomes (2r)² = 4r² → Force becomes F/4 = one-fourth. This is the direct application of the inverse square law.\n\n**(D) Half of original — INCORRECT:**\nHalf would apply if force followed a simple inverse law (F ∝ 1/r). But gravity follows F ∝ 1/r² (inverse SQUARE), so doubling distance gives 1/4, not 1/2.\n\n**Inverse square law summary for DRDO exam:**\n- Distance ×2 → Force ×(1/4)\n- Distance ×3 → Force ×(1/9)\n- Distance ×(1/2) → Force ×4\n- Distance ×(1/3) → Force ×9\n\n🔬 **DRDO Relevance:** The inverse square law governs satellite orbit calculations, gravitational slingshot manoeuvres for space probes, and the variation of g with altitude — all critical for DRDO's missile altitude-compensation algorithms and satellite orbit maintenance calculations."
