      "solution": "✅ **Correct Answer: (D) Reach at the same time**\n\n📚 **NCERT Mapping:** Class 11 Physics | Chapter 3 — Motion in a Straight Line | Topic: Free fall; Galileo's experiment; acceleration due to gravity is same for all bodies\n\n⭐ **Exam Relevance: Very High** — Galileo's famous experiment on free fall is one of the most tested physics concepts at all competitive exam levels. Pure conceptual understanding question — DRDO CEPTAM frequently tests this.\n\n---\n\n**Galileo's Principle of Free Fall:**\n\n**All objects, regardless of their mass, size, or material, fall with the same acceleration (g) in vacuum.**\n\nThis was famously demonstrated by **Galileo Galilei** at the Leaning Tower of Pisa (though this story may be apocryphal) and later confirmed by Newton's law of gravitation.\n\n**Mathematical proof:**\nGravitational force on object: F = mg\nNewton's 2nd Law: F = ma\n\nTherefore: mg = ma → **a = g**\n\nThe acceleration is independent of mass (m cancels). Every object falls with the same g ≈ 9.8 m/s² in vacuum.\n\n**Since all three (wood, wax, iron) fall from the same height with the same acceleration g, they all reach the ground at the same time.**\n\n---\n\n**(A) Wood — INCORRECT:**\nWood does not fall faster or slower than other materials in vacuum. In real air, wood might be affected slightly by air resistance depending on shape, but the question implies ideal free-fall conditions.\n\n**(B) Wax — INCORRECT:**\nSame reasoning. Wax has no special gravitational advantage over wood or iron.\n\n**(C) Iron — INCORRECT:**\nAlthough iron is much denser than wood or wax, density and mass do NOT affect the rate of fall in gravity. All three reach the ground simultaneously. (In air, iron being more compact might have slightly less air resistance for equal size, but the question is about gravity's effect — they reach at same time in free fall.)\n\n**(D) Reach at the same time — CORRECT:**\nAll three reach simultaneously because gravitational acceleration (g) is the same for all objects regardless of mass, density, or material. This is Galileo's law of free fall.\n\n**Famous demonstration:** On the Moon (no air resistance), astronaut David Scott dropped a hammer and a feather simultaneously in 1971 — both hit the Moon's surface at exactly the same time, beautifully confirming Galileo's principle.\n\n🔬 **DRDO Relevance:** Galileo's free fall principle is fundamental to DRDO's ballistic trajectory calculations — all projectiles (regardless of mass) experience the same gravitational acceleration, a key input in artillery fire control systems at TBRL (Terminal Ballistics Research Laboratory) and weapon systems developed at ARDE."
