      "solution": "✅ **Correct Answer: (A) Maximum at the poles**\n\n📚 **NCERT Mapping:** Class 11 Physics | Chapter 8 — Gravitation | Topic: Variation of g with latitude and altitude; weight = mg\n\n⭐ **Exam Relevance: Very High** — Variation of g with latitude is a standard exam topic. The reason why weight is maximum at poles and minimum at equator is tested in DRDO CEPTAM, UPSC, and SSC exams repeatedly.\n\n---\n\n**Why weight is maximum at the poles:**\n\n**Weight = mg** (weight depends on g)\n\n**Two reasons why g is maximum at poles:**\n\n**Reason 1 — Shape of Earth (Oblate Spheroid):**\nThe Earth is not a perfect sphere — it is slightly flattened at the poles and bulges at the equator.\n- Polar radius ≈ 6,356 km\n- Equatorial radius ≈ 6,378 km\n- Poles are closer to Earth's centre\n- Since g = GM/r², smaller r at poles → larger g at poles\n\n**Reason 2 — Earth's Rotation (Centrifugal Effect):**\nEarth rotates about its axis. Objects on the rotating Earth experience a centrifugal pseudo-force directed away from the axis.\n- At equator: maximum centrifugal effect (directly opposes gravity) → effective g is reduced\n- At poles: zero centrifugal effect (rotation axis passes through poles) → g is unaffected\n\n**Combined effect:**\n- g at poles ≈ 9.832 m/s²\n- g at equator ≈ 9.780 m/s²\n- Difference: ~0.5%\n\n**Therefore, weight (mg) is MAXIMUM at the poles and MINIMUM at the equator.**\n\n---\n\n**(A) Maximum at the poles — CORRECT:**\nBoth the shape factor (shorter polar radius) and the rotation factor (zero centrifugal effect at poles) make g maximum at poles. Hence weight is maximum at poles.\n\n**(B) Same everywhere — INCORRECT:**\ng (and hence weight) varies with latitude. This option contradicts the physics.\n\n**(C) Maximum at the equator — INCORRECT:**\nWeight is MINIMUM at the equator (maximum distance from Earth's centre + maximum centrifugal reduction of effective g).\n\n**(D) More on mountains than plains — INCORRECT:**\nOn mountains, altitude increases (r increases) → g decreases → weight DECREASES on mountains compared to plains at the same latitude. Weight is LESS on mountains, not more.\n\n🔬 **DRDO Relevance:** Variation of g with latitude affects **missile trajectory calculations** — DRDO's ballistic missiles (Agni series) must account for the slight variation in gravitational acceleration along their flight path from launch site to target, especially for inter-continental range. DRDL's guidance engineers include latitude corrections in the flight computer algorithms."
