      "solution": "✅ **Correct Answer: (B) Increase by 2%**\n\n📚 **NCERT Mapping:** Class 11 Physics | Chapter 8 — Gravitation | Topic: Acceleration due to gravity; g = GM/R²; variation with radius\n\n⭐ **Exam Relevance: Very High** — This calculation using the formula g = GM/R² is a standard IAS (Pre) and DRDO CEPTAM question. Tests mathematical application of gravitational formula with percentage change.\n\n---\n\n**Derivation:**\n\n**g = GM/R²**\n\nWhere G = gravitational constant (unchanged), M = mass of Earth (unchanged), R = radius of Earth.\n\nIf radius decreases by 1%:\nNew radius R' = R − 0.01R = R(1 − 0.01) = 0.99R\n\nNew g' = GM / (R')² = GM / (0.99R)² = GM / (0.9801R²)\n\n**g' = g / 0.9801 ≈ g × 1.0203**\n\n**Percentage increase in g = (g' − g)/g × 100 = (1.0203 − 1) × 100 ≈ 2.03% ≈ 2%**\n\n**Alternative approach using calculus (percentage change):**\ng = GM/R² → ln g = ln(GM) − 2 ln R\nDifferentiating: Δg/g = −2 ΔR/R\nIf ΔR/R = −1% (radius shrinks), then:\nΔg/g = −2 × (−1%) = **+2%**\n\ng INCREASES by **2%** when radius decreases by 1%.\n\n---\n\n**(A) Increase by 0.5% — INCORRECT:**\nWould arise if ΔR/R = −1% gives Δg/g = ½ × 1% — wrong exponent relationship.\n\n**(B) Increase by 2% — CORRECT:**\nSince g ∝ 1/R², and the exponent is 2, a 1% decrease in R gives a 2% increase in g. ✓\n\n**(C) Decrease by 0.5% — INCORRECT:**\nWhen R decreases, g INCREASES (they are inversely related). Decrease is wrong direction.\n\n**(D) Decrease by 2% — INCORRECT:**\nDirection is wrong — g increases when R shrinks, not decreases.\n\n**General rule:** Since g ∝ 1/R², every 1% change in R causes a **2% change** in g (in opposite direction).\n\n🔬 **DRDO Relevance:** Variation of g with Earth's radius is used in DRDO's **precise inertial navigation** calculations for long-range ballistic missiles (Agni-V) where even tiny gravitational variations affect accuracy over thousands of kilometres."
