      "solution": "✅ **Correct Answer: (D) Provides the necessary acceleration for its motion**\n\n📚 **NCERT Mapping:** Class 11 Physics | Chapter 8 — Gravitation | Topic: Orbital motion of satellites; centripetal acceleration; why satellites don't fall\n\n⭐ **Exam Relevance: Very High** — Why satellites don't fall is a classic conceptual question tested in UPSC IAS (Pre) and DRDO CEPTAM. Tests deep understanding of orbital mechanics — critical for DRDO's satellite-related work.\n\n---\n\n**Why a satellite does not fall down:**\n\nThe satellite DOES 'fall' — but it falls in a circular path (orbit) rather than straight down.\n\n**Earth's gravitational attraction provides the CENTRIPETAL ACCELERATION** needed to keep the satellite in circular orbit. The satellite is in continuous free fall toward Earth, but its horizontal velocity is so high that as it falls, Earth curves away beneath it — the satellite never reaches the surface.\n\n**Orbital condition:** Gravitational force = Centripetal force needed\n**GMm/r² = mv²/r**\n**v_orbital = √(GM/r)** (orbital velocity for circular orbit at radius r)\n\nAt the correct orbital velocity, the gravitational acceleration (g at that altitude) exactly equals the centripetal acceleration (v²/r) required for circular motion.\n\n---\n\n**(A) Gravity does not exist at such distance — INCORRECT:**\nGravity exists at all distances (it only becomes negligible at extremely large distances approaching infinity). Earth's gravity definitely acts on satellites at orbital altitudes (hundreds to thousands of km). In fact, gravity IS what keeps them in orbit.\n\n**(B) Neutralized by Moon's attraction — INCORRECT:**\nThe Moon's gravitational effect on Earth-orbiting satellites is extremely small and directionally variable (not consistently cancelling Earth's gravity). Earth's gravity is the dominant force on all Earth satellites. This option is physically incorrect.\n\n**(C) Provides necessary speed — INCORRECT:**\nGravity provides ACCELERATION (force/mass = acceleration), NOT speed directly. Speed must be given to the satellite initially by the launch rocket. Gravity then bends the trajectory into a circular orbit by providing centripetal acceleration.\n\n**(D) Provides necessary acceleration — CORRECT:**\nEarth's gravitational attraction acts as the **centripetal force/acceleration** directing the satellite continuously toward Earth's centre. This centripetal acceleration keeps the satellite moving in a curved (circular) path rather than flying off in a straight line. The satellite is in constant free fall but its horizontal speed prevents it from hitting the ground.\n\n🔬 **DRDO Relevance:** India's military satellites (RISAT, Cartosat for reconnaissance) orbit Earth using exactly this principle. DRDO collaborates with ISRO for military satellite applications, and understanding orbital mechanics is essential for satellite-based intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance (ISR) systems."
